<h1>Overview and Trends</h1>

<p><strong>Artificial intelligence (AI)</strong> broadly refers to computer systems that perform tasks commonly requiring human intelligence, such as reasoning or decision-making. Key subfields include machine learning (ML) – algorithms that learn from data without explicit instructions
     – and deep learning (DL), a form of ML using multi-layered neural networks to automatically extract complex patterns from raw data. A recent branch, generative AI, uses deep-learning models to create new content (e.g. text, images, audio) based on learned patterns. The following paragraphs and table summarize these concepts, with DL illustrated below:</p>

<p>Deep learning networks consist of many interconnected layers of “neurons” that transform input data into high-level representations. Each layer extracts increasingly abstract features (for example, early layers of an image model might detect edges or textures, later layers recognize shapes or faces). Generative AI models are a type of deep-learning system specifically trained to produce novel outputs.In summary, AI is the broad field of intelligent algorithms, ML is a subset where systems learn from data, DL is a specialized ML with deep neural nets, and generative AI is DL applied to content creation.</p>

